muros (0.9.37) trixie; urgency=medium

  * Unbound (recursive DNS): port the resolver integration from FreeBSD to
    Debian. The internal chroot is disabled (chroot: "") since the FreeBSD
    nullfs/devfs chroot under /var/unbound has no Debian equivalent and the mount
    sync is already a no-op; unbound now runs directly from its /var/unbound
    working directory as the unbound user. All control/check/anchor binaries use
    their Debian /usr/sbin paths.
  * Unbound: replace the missing unbound-anchor bootstrap with the maintained
    DNSSEC root key from the dns-root-data package (/usr/share/dns/root.key),
    and drop privileges with runuser instead of the FreeBSD "chroot -u user -g
    group /" idiom for unbound-control-setup.
  * Unbound: fix the FreeBSD "find -depth 1" calls in start.sh, which GNU find
    rejects, to "-mindepth 1 -maxdepth 1", and derive num-threads from nproc
    instead of the FreeBSD kern.smp.cpus sysctl.
  * Unbound: only load the embedded Python module (DNSBL) and emit the python:
    section when DNSBL is enabled. The Debian unbound build does not ship the
    unboundmodule.py helper the interpreter needs to bootstrap, so loading it
    unconditionally broke startup; gating it keeps the recursive resolver
    working out of the box (DNSBL stays a follow-up). Validated end to end under
    configd orchestration: the generated config passes unbound-checkconf,
    unbound binds :53 multi-threaded, and queries resolve with AD set.
  * Packaging: stop and disable the stock unbound/unbound-resolvconf systemd
    units (MurOS owns the resolver lifecycle) and disable the packaged AppArmor
    profile that would otherwise confine unbound to /etc/unbound and deny
    /var/unbound. Validated on Debian unbound 1.22: recursion resolves with the
    AD bit set (DNSSEC validated) and a deliberately broken DNSSEC zone is
    correctly rejected with SERVFAIL.

 -- MurOS <dev@muros.org>  Sun, 21 Jun 2026 09:45:00 +0000

muros (0.9.36) trixie; urgency=medium

  * IPsec: port the strongSwan integration from FreeBSD to Debian. Configuration
    now lives in the Debian default locations (/etc/strongswan.conf and
    /etc/swanctl, the swanctl defaults), the daemon is driven through systemd
    (charon-systemd via "systemctl start strongswan" plus an explicit
    "swanctl --load-all") instead of the legacy ipsec starter, and the
    swanctl/charon binaries use their /usr/sbin paths.
  * IPsec: drop the setkey based manual SPD code path. setkey is a FreeBSD/KAME
    tool with no Linux equivalent; the XFRM stack installs the policies charon
    negotiates directly through netlink. The manual SPD apply is now a no-op and
    the raw SAD/SPD diagnostic views degrade gracefully when setkey is absent.
  * IPsec: port routed IPsec (VTI) interface handling to Linux XFRM interfaces
    (ip link add type xfrm if_id <reqid>, ip address add ... peer ...) instead
    of the FreeBSD if_ipsec ifconfig reqid/tunnel calls.
  * IPsec: ship a strongswan.service drop-in that clears the packaged
    ExecStartPost=swanctl --load-all so an invalid generated connection can no
    longer take the whole daemon down; MurOS loads the configuration itself.
  * Packaging: promote strongswan, charon-systemd and strongswan-swanctl to
    Recommends so IPsec is available out of the box. Validated on Debian:
    strongSwan 6.0.1 loads a generated site-to-site PSK connection
    (swanctl --list-conns shows the IKEv2 tunnel), and XFRM interface creation
    with if_id works.

