 -- MurOS <dev@muros.org>  Sun, 21 Jun 2026 08:55:00 +0000

muros (0.9.32) trixie; urgency=medium

  * Captive portal: add native nftables enforcement, completing the data plane
    port. lib/cpfw.py gains build()/teardown(): the dedicated inet captiveportal
    table now carries three hook chains rebuilt atomically from the running
    config:
      - rdr (nat/prerouting): authenticated and allowed clients are returned
        untouched, everyone else has tcp 80/443 redirected to the local portal
        ports (zoneid+9000 / zoneid+8000).
      - gate (filter/forward): counts per client traffic, lets established,
        authenticated, allowed (address and MAC) and DNS/DHCP through and drops
        the rest, so unauthenticated clients cannot reach the network.
      - portal_in (filter/input): lets clients reach the local portal ports and
        core services.
    Member and accounting set elements are preserved across a rebuild.
  * New scripts/captiveportal/setup_fw.py reads the zones from /conf/config.xml,
    resolves their interface devices and per zone allowed v4/v6/MAC entries and
    applies the ruleset; disabled or removed zones are cleared. Exposed as the
    "captiveportal setup_fw" configd action.
  * ServiceController reconfigure now rebuilds the nftables enforcement instead
    of reloading the removed FreeBSD IPFW templates; the rc script applies it on
    start and tears the table down on stop.
  * Note: a subsequent unrelated filter reload (flush ruleset) still clears the
    table until the next captive portal reconfigure; hooking setup_fw into the
    main filter reload remains the final integration step.

 -- MurOS <dev@muros.org>  Sun, 21 Jun 2026 08:35:00 +0000

muros (0.9.31) trixie; urgency=medium

  * Captive portal: port the data plane off FreeBSD pf and ipfw to nftables.
    A new lib/cpfw.py owns a dedicated "inet captiveportal" table that is
    created idempotently: per zone membership sets (cp_<zone>_v4/v6) replace the
    pf tables, accounting sets (acc_<zone>_{in,out}_{v4,v6}) carry the counter
    flag in place of the ipfw 30000-50000 count rules, and a forward-hooked
    chain references the accounting sets so matched clients are counted.
  * lib/pf.py: PF.add_to_table/remove_from_table/list_table now manage the
    nftables membership sets, and state teardown uses conntrack -D (replacing
    pfctl -k) on client removal.
  * lib/ipfw.py: IPFW.add_accounting/del_accounting/list_accounting_info now
    read per element nftables counters. As nftables keeps no per element last
    access time, last_accessed is derived from byte deltas between polls and
    cached in /var/run/captiveportal/accounting.state, preserving idle timeout
    behaviour. Method signatures are unchanged so allow/disconnect/listClients
    and the background process keep working as is.
  * Note: authenticated clients are now tracked and accounted natively; wiring
    the redirect and pass rules that reference cp_<zone> sets into the main
    nft_build ruleset remains a follow-up.

