muros (0.9.28) trixie; urgency=medium

  * Fix the whole dashboard failing to load ("Failed to load widget" on every
    widget) and the UI taking around ten seconds per request. The configd
    control plane, which backs every dashboard widget and settings-apply action
    over its local socket, was installed with systemd start suppressed
    (dh_installsystemd --no-start), so apt never started it on install and never
    restarted it on upgrade. Whenever it was not running, the PHP client waited
    out its ten second connect timeout on every call and the widgets errored.
    configd is now started on install and restarted on upgrade (it only listens
    on a unix socket, so this never touches the management link), and postinst
    enables and restarts it explicitly as a safeguard.

 -- MurOS <dev@muros.org>  Sun, 21 Jun 2026 07:05:00 +0000

muros (0.9.27) trixie; urgency=medium

  * Performance: backend actions (applying settings, dashboard widgets, any
    operation routed through the configd action layer) were slow because the
    CLI PHP processes that configd spawns per action had no opcode cache and
    recompiled the whole codebase every time. OPcache was previously enabled
    for the FPM web pool only, which fixed login latency but not actions. The
    CLI SAPI now uses a persistent on-disk OPcache (opcache.file_cache under
    /var/lib/php/opcache), which a short-lived process can reuse across
    invocations. Compiling the full code set drops from roughly 600 ms to about
    50 ms, so per-action latency is cut by an order of magnitude.
  * Diagnostics: three ported backend scripts (system/diag_disk.py,
    diagnostics/empty_json.py, interfaces/netstat_interfaces.py) had lost their
    executable bit, so configd could not run them and returned exit status 126.
    This broke the Disk dashboard widget and a few diagnostics actions and made
    the dashboard retry failing requests. The executable bit is restored.

