 -- MurOS <dev@muros.org>  Sat, 20 Jun 2026 13:00:00 +0200

muros (0.9.12) trixie; urgency=medium

  * Network Time (NTP) ported from the ntp.org daemon to chrony, the time
    daemon MurOS already ships on Debian. ntpd is not packaged for Debian and
    its configuration and query interfaces differ from chrony. ntpd_configure_do
    now generates /etc/chrony/chrony.conf from the Ntpd model (upstream servers
    and pools with iburst/prefer/noselect, orphan/local stratum, serve-to-client
    via allow, per-interface bindaddress, statistics logging, leap second list,
    rate limiting and custom options) and drives the stock chrony systemd unit;
    the former one-shot client mode maps to chronyd -q. GPS and PPS refclocks are
    mapped to chrony SHM/PPS refclocks (best effort, needs gpsd and hardware).
  * The Network Time status page (ntpd_status.php) now reads chrony instead of
    ntpq: it parses chronyc sources, sourcestats and tracking into the same
    fields the existing view expects (status symbols, stratum, poll in seconds,
    octal reach, and offset/jitter/delay in milliseconds), with per-source round
    trip delay taken from chronyc ntpdata. Validated against live chrony and the
    generated config validated with chronyd -p.
  * The NTP service now tracks /run/chrony/chronyd.pid and stops cleanly through
    systemctl. Serial line setup for GPS uses stty instead of the FreeBSD
    comcontrol/tip path and accepts Debian tty device names.

 -- MurOS <dev@muros.org>  Sat, 20 Jun 2026 12:55:19 +0200

muros (0.9.11) trixie; urgency=medium

  * Kea DHCP server ported to Debian. OPNsense drives Kea through the FreeBSD
    keactrl/rc.d mechanism, which does not exist on Debian; the config layout
    and binary paths also differ. The Kea config generators now write to the
    Debian-native /etc/kea (the stock daemons and their AppArmor profiles only
    allow that path), the control sockets use the canonical /run/kea path that
    Kea 2.6 validates (it rejects the /var/run symlink form), and the hook
    libraries are loaded from the multiarch hooks directory. The ISC premium
    libdhcp_host_cmds.so hook (not packaged for Debian) is dropped; host
    reservations are written into the subnet configuration directly.
  * Generated Kea configuration is now written 0640 root:_kea so the daemon
    user can read it while the secrets (DDNS TSIG keys, HA) stay protected.
  * New kea_service.sh wrapper drives the stock kea-dhcp4/6, ctrl-agent and
    dhcp-ddns systemd units from the enabled flags rendered into keactrl.conf,
    starting only the daemons enabled in the UI and stopping the rest. The Kea
    configd actions (start/stop/restart/status) now call it instead of the
    FreeBSD rc.d script and pluginctl.
  * Add the Kea daemon packages to Depends and disable the stock units on
    install so MurOS owns their lifecycle. Lease listing keeps working over the
    dhcp4/dhcp6 control sockets (lease_cmds hook), validated end to end.

 -- MurOS <dev@muros.org>  Sat, 20 Jun 2026 12:33:18 +0200

muros (0.9.10) trixie; urgency=medium

  * Gateway monitoring now functional on Debian. The gateway-monitoring path
    (dpinger.inc, gateway_status.php, gateway_watcher.php) and the monitor host
    route (system_host_route via iproute2) were already OS-independent; the only
    missing piece was the daemon. dpinger 3.6 is now packaged for Debian 13 and
    pulled in as a dependency, so per-gateway latency, loss and availability
    monitoring (the basis for multi-WAN failover) work out of the box.
  * Add dpinger to Depends (served from the MurOS apt repository).
  * Interactive first-boot console (OPNsense-style). The appliance console
    (local VGA tty1 and the first serial port) now autologin as root into the
    MurOS console. On first boot a one-time wizard runs: keyboard layout, then
    interface assignment (setports) and interface IP address (setaddr: static
    IP, mask, gateway or DHCP). Hostname, DNS, timezone and language stay in
    the web setup wizard. Each console step is skippable to keep the factory
    default, so a headless boot is never blocked.
  * Console menu fixes: provide /usr/local/bin/php (the FreeBSD interpreter
    path used by the ported shebangs) so the menu scripts run, and use
    /bin/bash for the shell option instead of the absent /bin/csh.

